surely will trigger a Great Depression, if we're lucky. There are many other reasons,
similarly inevitable, why the U.S. will remain the global superpower well beyond our
lifetimes. The shale revolution has pushed North America within 2 million barrels per
day of outright oil independence. And we now have the lowest electricity prices, nonsubsidized
-- in the world. The U.S. is home to nearly half of global consumer spending,
double that of the combined BRICs. The Navy has a 10:1 ratio, conservatively, in terms
of global firepower. And the commitment of that imbalance to the global commons is
